\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
Can you say something about working with John?  I mean, obviously he took your comments seriously. What was it like?  Was it an equal kind of partnership, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
Well, I mean, as you know, John is not the easiest person in the world to work with.  I think it\rquote s felt that Sally Tomlinson and I were the two who were able to establish the best relationships with him.  I think I only had one really fla
ming row with him, but that was after Sparkbrook.  It was clearly an unequal relationship because he was a very distinguished sociologist and I was just a new researcher.  But he had almost - I sensed a slight respect for me, because as he\rquote 
s said many times since, he said, \'93You\rquote ve got a nose for trouble.\'94  (LAUGHS)  And I\rquote m one of these people who doesn\rquote t hesitate to poke my nose in where it\rquote s clearly going to be very unwelcome, and where I\rquote 
m going to discover things that people would rather I didn\rquote t discov
er!  So I was a fairly bold fieldworker, and I think he liked that, and I think he liked my kind of disciplined approach. Again, it was fieldwork in an afternoon and evening, and then mornings typing up field notes in my office.  And I had that kind of ro
utine, and I worked very hard, I have to say.  I did a very long day\rquote s work.  And, of course, all my field notes were typed up on a little typewriter.
