Was the Sparkbrook Association mainly white English, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
The people who ran it were, but its clientele was very mixed.  I can\rquote 
t remember very many English people coming to the Association, but I think they probably had their well-established networks, it was the newcomers who needed the Association.  But the thing about Sparkbrook, in those days, was t
hat it was quite easy to meet people on the streets, you know, there were just a lot of people out and about, and you could say hello to somebody, you could fall in \endash  particularly with British people \endash 
 walk along beside them on the pavement and chat, and then just go off to do whatever else you were doing. So I didn\rquote t have any sort of strategy which said, \'93Right.  Now I\rquote m going to interview ten English origin people\'94, you know, \'93
Five women, five men\'94.  I just let it happen, and I think I met quite a lot of them that way.
