\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid12190969 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
The English, on the whole, not.  No.  The English are perhaps a bit more reserved.  It was the minorities who were the most hospitable.  No, I didn\rquote t enjoy any very close relations with English families in Sparkbrook.  And I didn\rquote 
t experience much hostility either.  I can\rquote t remember the name of the woman who used to write the letters now, but I kind of rubbed along with her and she was typical of raci
sts at the time.  You got talking to her, and she was going on about all these West Indians and all the terrible things they did, and then you said, \'93But, look, your next door neighbours are West Indian\'94.  \'93Oh well, he\rquote s different.  He
\rquote s a real gent.  He\rquote s a real gentleman\'94
.  It was very hard not to intervene.  I intervened almost inadvertently really, because I remember talking to her, and she said how unfriendly and stand-offish the Pakistani men were, and they were really not very nice people at all, and so on, and she
\rquote d obviously tried to befriend them, and I said to her, \'93Look, these people have as much difficulty with your culture as you do with theirs\'94.  I said, \'93There are quite a few people, quite a few men, who migrated to Sparkbrook, who don
\rquote t really know how to deal with women outside their family.  They don\rquote t know how to relate to strange women\'94.  I thought she was a pretty strange woman!  So I said, you know, \'93Why don\rquote t you understand?\'94  I said, \'93It
\rquote s not that you\rquote re having difficulty with them\'94, I said, \'93they\rquote re having difficulty with you\'94.  \'93Oh!\'94 she said, \'93I never thought of that!\'94  She said, \'93Now you\rquote ve said it, yes, I can see that\'94
.  And I thought, \'93Oh well, now the participant observer has intervened\'94.  But, I couldn\rquote t not have that discussion with her.  How much it modified her view, I don\rquote t know, but, \'93Oh, yeah, yeah.  I hadn\rquote t thought of that\'94.

