\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
Right.  I think I met my first West Indians through John Rex, who had met a young couple, the woman was a schoolteacher.  Oh, that was the other way I met English people, by schoolteachers.  And I started off with this young couple who\rquote 
d actually just moved out of Sparkbrook to the suburbs, but they knew people in Sparkbrook still, and they provided me with an entr\'e9
e to meet various people.  And again, the churches were quite important there.  But the Sparkbrook Association also had a West Indian clientele, including the people who were organising the Caribbean Football League.  And so that gave me all sorts 
of ready-made contacts.  Although I don\rquote 
t know anything about football, I could get them to talk to me about football, and how they played out inter-island rivalries on the football pitch.  And then in the churches it was very straightforward to talk to th
em.  Well, straightforward in the Methodist Church, because I\rquote m a Methodist, and that all clicked.  Some of the more Evangelical churches I found a bit tough-going, particularly when half way through a service, people would say, \'93
And would you like to say a few words to the congregation?\'94 to which I normally said, \'93No thank you.  Not today\'94.  But, you know, people would chat afterwards, and I\rquote d arrange to go and meet them and so on.
