\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid16655669 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Well, you just imagine sitting talking to somebody explaining their marginality.  It was a case study of a zone of tra
nsition. The West Indian schoolteacher I started off with was the absolute opposite.  They had used Sparkbrook as a stepping-stone, they got a cheap house.  Now they were in a nice house in the suburbs, you know, had a job, you know, respectable occupatio
n, they had moved in.  They had been marginal, perhaps, in Sparkbrook, but they\rquote d moved into the mainstream.  This guy had been in the mainstream \endash  family, Army, British Legion \endash 
 and now he was sliding out and, you know, one started thinking about the work of the Chicago School }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16655669\charrsid14902524 and the \lquote marginal man\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
, and he was right on the fringe.  You could see him teetering along the fringe.  So he was a fascinating person.  Maybe that particular interview didn\rquote t generate a lot of data, but by Heavens, he was theoretical
ly stimulating!  You know, you walked out of that pub and your brain was in theoretical overdrive!  He would never have known that!  (LAUGHS)  I used to say to John that when I was in Sparkbrook I was always thinking theory, and when I was back in my offi
ce, trying to do the theory, I wanted to get back into Sparkbrook.  But Sparkbrook was a very Durkheimian experience.  I kept on asking the question, \'93What is holding this together?\'94  Or, \'93To what extent is this being held together, and by what?
\'94  Because Durkheim was working in a society that was in a state of virtual disintegration, and certainly catastrophic change, so was Sparkbrook.  And I thought, \'93Well, Durkheim\rquote s lurking round every corner here\'94. I didn\rquote 
t see myself as a Durkheimian, but whatever you think of the answers that Durkheim came up with, the problems that he tackled were there in the pubs, on the streets, in the churches, in Sparkbrook.  I thought, \'93Well, Durkheim should be alive and here!
\'94  But it was just me.  So the man in the Brewers\rquote  Arms may not have generated reams and reams of data, but he was a trem}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16655669\charrsid14902524 
endous intellectual challenge.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
Now, the other marginal man - before I tell you about the other ethnic minorities - was Alec.  Alec was I think an Estonian, probably a refugee.  He was a 
lonely man, living in Sparkbrook, and he had no friends or family there, and he latched on to the Sparkbrook Association as somewhere, at last, he has somebody to talk to, somebody who\rquote 
d listen to him.  And he had an alcohol problem.  He used to go to Yates\rquote s Wine Lodge in the centre of Birmingham and drink himself into oblivion.  And we used to sit and talk to him when he was sober enough, and quite often he\rquote 
d come into the Sparkbrook Association and they\rquote d sober him up.  And he was a real lost soul.  He w
as so grateful for the people in the Association talking to him, taking him seriously, chatting to him, and he wanted to do something in return, always, and he wanted to do the most insane things in return!  (LAUGHS)  Like he decided, one day, he\rquote 
d clean the windows for them.  So he turned up with a ladder to do the upstairs windows.  Well, of course, he was incredibly hungover!  And you wouldn\rquote 
