\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Right.  I had to be careful about this, because the population was, as I\rquote ve indicated, divided, and the Methodists regarded the Working Men
\rquote s Club in the main town \endash  Esh Winning \endash  as almost the anti-chambe
r to hell.  You know, it was only the - if not the damned, the people on their way to damnation were in the Club: proper people were in the chapel.  And although they more or less understood what I was doing \endash 
 and they were very keen to tell me their story, they thought they had a wonderful story to tell. I never ever went into the Club, because I thought that would create - I\rquote 
d have to explain all sorts of awkward things.  So I kept out of the Club, but I was able to locate various people in the population
 who I knew to be quite vociferous critics of the Methodists, and who had interesting things to say about the history of the village, and who\rquote d been, for example, heavily involved in the 1926 lockout of the miners, and who\rquote 
d had interesting political careers So that kind of [sample] - I suppose the term today would be \'93snowball\'94
. It was easy contacting people within the Methodist population, that was easy, I was invited into dozens of houses to have tea and to talk to them, and I was invited to talk to Meth
odist gatherings and so on.  But for the non-Methodists I used this kind of snowball tactic, and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7550708\charrsid14902524  it seemed to work quite well.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Again, the Waterhouses Pit was open when I started work, but it closed very shortly afterwards.  The Esh Winning Pit remained op
en a bit longer, so I was able to make some contacts through the mine and the miners. So I wasn\rquote t confined to the Methodists.  As I say, the Methodists were easy, and unlike almost any other research experience I\rquote 
ve had, the Methodists were very eager to talk to me, and they could hardly wait for me to come round and talk to them!  (LAUGHS)  And that was easy.  But it was too easy!  I can\rquote 
t remember whether I recount this in the book, but a particular population actually develops its own story about itself, which is shared in common, and the unwary researcher may think they\rquote re getting an individual\rquote 
s account.  Now, what happened was, there had been a very scandalous event in the Methodist population in, I think, the 1920s, involving a local preacher and a gi
rl in the choir.  It was kind of shock horror, and even in the 1960s people were a bit reluctant to talk about it, and I just wondered whether there were relatives still around.  I don\rquote 
t know.  But when I did broach this subject, I got kind of the same account, people told me the same things, and I thought, \'93Good!\'94, you know, \'93I\rquote m getting the story of what happened\'94.  And one day I was going home on the 44 bus, and I
\rquote d been interviewing a woman from the Methodist Chapel, and she had told me about this event, and I thought, \'93Now, that\rquote s odd!  This woman can\rquote t be old enough to remember that event.  Perhaps she\rquote s heard it from somebody\'94
.  Anyhow, later on, in my archival research in one of the Durham newspapers, in the 1920s I found a little report about these 
scandalous events in this village, and the newspaper report was word for word what all the individual people had told me in their interviews.  So what I was getting from the village was not necessarily first-hand accounts of people who were involved or en
gaged, but they were feeding back to me press reports which they had read, or had been passed down to them.  And that was a very sharp cautionary tale, for a still quite a young researcher.  Wow!  I thought I was getting - I was triangulating, \'93
Everybody was telling me the same story, so it must be true!\'94
  Well, it probably was true, but they were not independent accounts.  It was the agreed version.  They probably agreed the version when they gave it to the press!  So that was very interesting.
