ind\'94. But you could almost feel there was something that wasn\rquote t the property either of individuals or of the collectivity.  I don\rquote 
t know what it was.  Some kind of emotional current.  This is what religious and ritual events, when Durkheim talks about \endash  I forget the terms he uses now \endash 
 but these forces take over, that seem almost to come from outside you.  You got this at this village funeral.  I\rquote m still not sure who it was who\rquote d died.  Everybody turned out.  And I was told that all village funerals were li
ke that.  So I kept very careful notes of that funeral \endash  who I saw there, and the numbers that were there and so on, and the fact that there were people who I had never ever seen in the chapel, packed }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9966519\charrsid14902524 in.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Then the other thing that happened were just the S
unday Services, and these were getting - the attendances were going down, the nu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid9966519\charrsid14902524 mbers were dwindling.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 I remember interviewing an old chap who was, again, very old, and I almost had to decide who I was going to interview next, in terms of how old people were, because I didn\rquote 
