\endash  but Tom Greener\rquote s family, like many of the families that I got to know, had this ambivalence about coal mining.  They were very proud to be miners, it was a man\rquote 
s life.  They would talk about how much coal they could hew, about what they contributed to the War, and to the building of modern Britain \endash  all that sort of stuff \endash  and at the same time they would say they didn\rquote 
t want their sons to go down the pit, because it was a rotten life. It was hard work, and you got no thanks for it, and it was dangerous, and it was dirty and so on.  And one or two of them told me that there were guide books written in the 19}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\super\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
 century which told travellers how to avoid mining villages \endash  because there were some savage people!  So they were proud of being miners, but they didn\rquote t really want their sons \endash  if they could possibly avoid it \endash 
