Also, that in this particular area, the mine owners were all good Non-Conformists, and quite paternalistic towards their employees, so you didn\rquote t get that development of class consciousness that you might have got, say, in som
e of the Scottish pits, or in South Wales.  Before the development of the sort of joint stock companies, and the big take-overs and amalgamations, it seems that some of these Non-Conformist coal owners were actually quite good men, and they tried to look 
after their workforce, within the limits of the ethos of that age.  So when people started talking about how awful Tony Blair was and so on, I used to say to them, \'93He is the inheritor of the real Labour tradition.  It\rquote 
s that Methodist/Gladstonian Liberal-Labour tradition. Because the people who won, in those mining villages, were not the ILP Socialists, it was the old Gladstonian Liberals who\rquote 
d gradually moved across and become the stalwarts of the Labour Party, but they were still, deep down, Gladstonian Liberals.
