{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 The Deerness Valley was a particular kind of mining area, quite different from the Durham East, and the coast, and it\rquote 
s just a geological thing.  I suspect that had I done the study, say, over in Easington or somewhere, where the pits ope
ned later, I might have had a slightly different story.  The other point, I suppose, of note, is that I became aware of the role of migration in the development of coal mining, that the real skilled workers, the face workers, the underground workers, were
 descended from the Weardale and Teesdale lead miners who had, themselves, been tin miners in Cornwall. So there\rquote d been this great migration from the tin mines to the lead mines, to the coal mines.  And then \endash 
 and here we come back to the race relations thi
ng - the unskilled work, like sinking shafts, that was done by Irish unskilled labourers who were on much lower pay.  The miners, the face-workers, they ate beef once a week, at a time when I suspect the majority of the British working class did not, when
 the staple diet was herring and pork and what have you.  So the labour elite were defined by religion, but they had also descended from highly mobile workers. And in the mining slump, some of those workers went off to the States, and although I didn
\rquote t follow this through, I think some of them picked up on syndicalism and so on in the States, which they then brought back to the Scottish coal fields \endash  but that\rquote s anoth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13633050\charrsid14902524 er story that I didn\rquote t pursue.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
So perhaps not much more to say about the Deerness Valley.  But you cannot do fieldwork in as rich an environment as that without all sorts of other issues, that you\rquote 
re never going to have time to pursue, being thrown up.  And one could go back to that material and think about it, and re-work it for another lifetime
.  However, you could never do the fieldwork again.  I mean, I interviewed men who had gone down the mine at the age of 14.  I interviewed men who worked below ground before 1900 \endash  not many, I think two \endash  who\rquote d gone d}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13633050\charrsid14902524 own as, literally, as \lquote trapper boys\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524  th
at you read about in the history books, working the ventilator doors.  Now, I got to those people just in time.  And what a privilege that was!  What did I miss in all the people who had already gone?  One can never know, but I did collect that, at the ve
ry end I got that bit of history.  But it wasn\rquote t just history.  I mean, it was riveting sociology to me.  If you\rquote d said to me, \'93Are you doing history or sociology?\'94 I\rquote d have said \'93Yes\'94.
