\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Why is that?  Why don
\rquote t you think you were a good father?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
Oh, I think I was too much the Naval officer.  My wife says that I\rquote m really not attuned to the nuances of familial interpersonal relations.  She\rquote s got used to it, but, of course, you can\rquote 
t expect young children fully to understand that.  Also I think I was so committed to my work, I probably missed out on many things that I might have done with the children.  But my son paid me a compliment.  I don\rquote t think 
he intended to, but I took it as a compliment!  I was very touched. I made some comment about how well he was doing and so on, and we got into some sort of discussion about education, and he said, \'93
Well, when I was little, if ever I asked you a question, you didn\rquote t just give me the answer, you showed me there was an even more interesting question behind it\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 That\rquote 
s wonderful!
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13633050 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 And I thought, \'93Wow!  Perhaps I wasn\rquote t all that bad after all!\'94  (LAUGHS)  And he just said that, and I thought, \'93Gosh!\'94
  I felt really moved by that comment.  My daughter - the two of them are very unalike, and she is incredible at interpersonal [relations], she can read every nuance, and when you see her handling the children, whereas I would wade in and there would be
 a flaming row, she moves around, heads things off, calms things down, and handles things beautifully \endash 
 not just with her own children, but I imagine with children in her classes as well.  She can foresee where things are going, and steer them.  And wherev
er she goes, she has an amazing network of friends, so almost within days of arriving in two new locations when she moved house, she already had a network of babysitters!  You know, I mean, she just makes friends and draws them in around her.  It\rquote 
s quite astonishing.  And her husband is, in a way, himself a bit unusual \endash  for men \endash  in that he\rquote s very very family-centred.  He\rquote 
s part of quite a big family network, and he clearly puts family ahead of everything.  When he comes home at night, that\rquote s the end of work, he never brings work home, except when he\rquote 
s actually working at home, in which case he locks himself in one of the rooms in the house, the family aren\rquote t allowed in.  He spends a lot of time with family, visiting family, doing things with family, in a w
ay that I never did.  So my daughter and her family now are incredibly good at human relations, and very sensitive, both of them, whereas I\rquote m a bit ham-fisted. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13633050\charrsid14902524  My son is a bit \lquote hail fellow, well met\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
, although he is quite sensitive.  He pretends not to be, but he\rquote s very kind of ethical. He\rquote s got a big contract at the moment with the MOD, and he clearly thought through the ethical implications of that very carefully, and that\rquote 
s a very big valuable contract \endash  I think it runs to millions.  And he\rquote s got some Civil Service contracts where they\rquote re handling the reorganisation, the downsizing of the Civil Service.  But I don\rquote t think he\rquote 
d work for an arms manufacturer.  So although he just gives this sort of very bluff - you know, he likes rock\rquote n\rquote roll, which I absolutely loathe!  I have well worked out sociological views about rock\rquote n\rquote 
roll!  And he likes his glass of beer and so on, whereas I\rquote m a teetotaller. So we\rquote re very different.  But I know that underlying that there is a man who has ethics and morals, and isn\rquote t 
just an entrepreneur.  He has values.  And if I have contributed to that, that\rquote s great.  Maybe his mother has contributed more, I don\rquote t know.  But that\rquote s nice to see in one\rquote s children, but one doesn\rquote 
t dwell on it with them.  So that\rquote s all I\rquote ve really got to say about my children.  We\rquote re very proud of them.
