e University, of course, is a very old university, very fine library, and Aberdeen, I felt, was a really great place to be an academic.  You could work quietly with a brilliant library, and just a very very nice environment.  However, there was a bit of a
 problem for me as a sociologist with my interests, in that I couldn\rquote 
t have been further away from issues surrounding race relations, and initially, labour migration.  So I was a bit stuck out on a limb in terms of my interests, so I started writing on immigration policy. I worked with Tina Wallace who\rquote 
d been a student of mine in Durham, on a book called, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Slamming the Door: The Administration of Immigration Control}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 .  Now, that was the only book on that topic in Britain, and it didn\rquote t get a single review, and
 thereafter it was heavily plagiarised by journalists. The publishers were constantly getting requests from journalists for free copies of it, and I read passages in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 The Observer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
, which had clearly been lifted straight from the book, but it was never acknowledged.  And I was a bit cross about that, because I thought it was an important book, and that may have been why it didn\rquote 
t get much mention, because it really lifted the lid - everybody knew that immigration law was getting increasingly restrictive and harsh, but what they didn\rquote 
t realise, was how that harshness and brutality was being amplified in the actual administration of the law \endash  behind the scenes, as it were \endash  and that was what that book was about.  And Tina had been working in Kenya, or Uganda, I 
forget now, and she could bring first-hand experience of what happened during the Idi Amin expulsions.  So I thought that was a reasonably important book which lifted the corner on some pretty nasty goings on.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
