\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid13633050 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Ah, well, now that\rquote s a v
ery interesting story.  I was approached by a publisher who said they would like to produce a short book on race relations that would sell on railway bookstalls.  So I thought, \'93Crikey!  I\rquote ve never been asked for that before!\'94
  So I sat down, and I wrote it.  I think I wrote it in about a week!  Now, that actually became something of a best-seller, and I\rquote ve met lots of people who\rquote ve said, particularly black people, who have said, \'93
Oh, I read that when I was at college\'94.  \'93Oh, are you the chap that wrote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Race and the Black Resistance}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 ?\'94 And it was the last academic book to sell for under \'a31 \endash  it was 75p, paperback, when it first came out.  However, it didn\rquote 
t come out with the publisher who commissioned it, because when the manuscript went in, it was picked up 
by one of the directors, [who] read it, and was a bit worried about what he thought was the very radical tone of the book, and he gave it to a Tory friend to read.  And this Tory friend \endash  I don\rquote t know who it was \endash  read it, and said, 
\'93Well, if anything, I think the author has really rather understated the general awfulness of the situation in Britain today\'94, and the publishers dropped it like a hot brick.  And I was then approached by another publisher who said they\rquote 
d like to take it up, providing I could write a chapter \endash  which I\rquote d been asked specifically not to write in the original \endash  on race relations in employment.  So I wrote an additional chapter for Plut}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid13633050\charrsid14902524 o Press, and it was published.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
Now, if you think about, supposing you were challenged to write a book about a field in which you think you have a lot to say, quite a bit of knowledge and expertise, and you\rquote 
re asked to write no more than about 80,000 or 100,000 words, in a format that can be sold from railway bookstalls.  You can only do that if you can 
develop a strong theoretical framework, otherwise what are you going to say?  And I think, in a number of respects, that book is one of the most theoretical books.  And I didn\rquote t sit down and say, \'93What\rquote s the theory going to be?\'94
  I realised, when I read it through, that I had to organise my thoughts to compress a lot of material and to simplify it.  And, in fact, I constructed a kind of theoretical framework in which to do that.  So that was a very interesting book to write. 

