\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
Well, it certainly didn\rquote t come from me, but I think it was probably some ideas that were in the background, and, if you like, in the back of John Rex\rquote 
s head, which very quickly came to the fore once we encountered what we saw in Sparkbrook.  You know there\rquote s been a long debate about this, over consumption classes and so on, particularly with Peter Saunders the way in which one\rquote 
s position in, if you like, the consumption market, might relate to or modify one\rquote s position in the class structure. We weren\rquote t actually saying that housing classes became a substitute for occupational 
classes, but we were saying - well, it depends exactly how you read Weber.  He talks about property classes, but does he mean property\rquote s capacity to generate income, or does he just mean classes of property ownership }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 per se}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 ?  But that was where this debate
 found its point of origin, and where it was located.  We weren\rquote t suggesting it was a substitute for traditional views of class structure.  And it was particularly relevant in Birmingham because it was a period of very high employment, Birmingham
\rquote s problem was getting enough workers in, which it wanted to do without building any houses for them. So many of the traditional class conflict issues, didn\rquote 
t arise.  What differentiated people was their capacity to house themselves, and the kind of property relations that they finished up with.  And that, in a way, const}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid11959815\charrsid14902524 ructed what Weber called their \lquote life chances\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
.  That term is much abused now, including by Conservative politicians and others, but that came out of a very Weberian context. I agree with some of our 
critics.  We were talking about a particular city at a particular point in its history, and with a particular mix of industries.  Had we been writing about, say, Bradford, I\rquote m not sure we\rquote 
d have come up with quite the same theoretical framework.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 But it\rquote 
