t, I was told I should get a better agent!  So the basic idea was that the University was in a very exploitative role vis-\'e0-vis the local black population, and was not to be trusted, and w}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10837068\charrsid14902524 as not to be co-operated with.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
However, I later got below and beyond that layer of the black population, and met other black people, and one of the best analyses of the situation came from an elderly retired black man who\rquote d worked on the railways in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10837068\charrsid14902524 Liverpool, and he talked about \lquote the damp course\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 .  Now, we all know what a damp course is in a building.  He typified the self-appointed local black leadership}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10837068\charrsid14902524  as \lquote the damp course\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 , and he explained it as follows.  
\'93They ensured that the needs and aspirations of the ordinary people in Liverpool 8, didn\rquote 
t ever get up to people in positions of authority.  And they ensured that none of the resources coming down from the top ever found their way to people at grass roots\'94.  And I thought that was a brilliant analysis, and I\rquote ve never been able to us
e it in a book or article, but that is lovely.  And, of course, what he was describing was, to my view, a leadership that had derived, in a way, from the resistance at the time of the so-called Liverpool Riots.  They had become the kind of leadership that
 
had professionalized itself and made its living out of the victim status of the black population of Liverpool, and whenever you tried, at conferences and things, whenever you tried to get them talking about any issues about race, they would keep on coming
 back to how they were the victims of racism and racial exploitation, and they would bang on and on and on about it and they would never move forward.  It was that harping on about the victim status of the population that they claimed to represent th}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10837068\charrsid14902524 at was their bread and butter.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
There was a funny incident - well, it wasn\rquote t funny really, but a speaker came to the Caribbean Centre from South Africa, and his father was on Robben Island with Nelson Mandela, so, clearly, this chap\rquote s family were deeply embedded 
in the fight against apartheid. And when he asked for questions after his talk, somebody got up and said how dare he come to Liverpool 8 and talk about racism.  He couldn\rquote 
t possibly know anything about racism, having never lived and been in Liverpool 8.  S
o that was the kind of attitude that one encountered!  It was very backward-looking, and yet one could see there were material interests embedded in that kind of outlook.  And one of the things I should talk about later is the inability of anybody to deal
 with that effectively \endash  either from wi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid16468903\charrsid14902524 thin the community or outside.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 So there we were.  I was clearly not going to be making any progress there.  It\rquote s not that I didn\rquote 
t try.  You probably know this joke, but it constantly came back to me in those desperat
e years, about the black man who went to register the vote in Alabama, and they asked him, could he read?  So he read a bit from the newspaper, and they then asked him what the square root of nine was, and he told them.  And they asked him what the Sevent
h Amendment to the US Constitution was, they asked him about the Gettysburg Address, and he gave them the whole Address, and then they said, \'93Can you read this?\'94 and they handed him a Chinese newspaper, and he said, \'93Yep!\'94  And they said, \'93
Okay, what does it say?\'94  And he said, \'93It says \lquote there\rquote s one nigger that ain\rquote t gonna get the vote today!\rquote \'94  And that\rquote 
s how I felt in Liverpool!  Here was one sociologist who was never going to do research!  So the other thing that I did towards the end of my time there was
 to concentrate on the work that I could do without going out into the field, if you like, and I began to look at the Census data, at the Sample of Anonymised Records, and later at the longitudinal data, so I moved into a field that was really quite new t
o me - well, no, not new, but one that I hadn\rquote t really given much attention to, where I actually found myself doing some heavy number crunching and statistical tests that I\rquote 
d only ever read about, and I enjoyed that.  It meant I made new colleagues, and I became a member of the Radical Statistics Group, whose conference I\rquote 
m going to tomorrow.  And I learnt a hell of a lot about the strengths and weaknesses of that kind of research.  I went on a course on logistic regression, about six months before I retired
, and I happened to mention this to a group of students, undergraduates, and they were absolutely staggered!  They couldn\rquote 
t understand why anybody would want to go on a training course just before they retired!  And I was able to point out to them that edu
cation was exciting and life-long.  So I had that sort of little boost to a part of my career that I had never really anticipated. I don\rquote t think I\rquote 
m terribly good at it, actually, I really do struggle with logistic regression, and try and avoid it whenever possible, but}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid6637681\charrsid14902524 
 there are things to be learnt.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
One of the things I did around about the time I retired, was to produce a deprivation atlas for Flintshire County Council, which used both Census and administrative data to produce quite a fat book of maps and
 tables written and produced in a way which I hoped even Councillors could understand, and technically quite interesting, because we produced it in colour, but we had to find a colour scheme that would photocopy without all going black or all going white.
 
 So I produced this report for Flintshire, which was a very big advance on a Census atlas that I produced for Grampian Region after the 1981 Census, which was done in black and white, on a mainframe computer where you waited ages and ages for your output 
a
nd so on.  So that was a good exercise.  Needless to say, the atlas sunk without any trace, whatsoever, into the entrails of Flintshire County Council, and when I asked them if they wanted one done on the 2011 Census, nobody had heard of the one I did for
 the 2001 Census!  But they don\rquote t even have a statistician.  So those were some of the things I did in that transitional phase between full-time employment as an academic sociologist, and retirement as a full-time sociologist.  It\rquote 
s very clear, I think, that I don\rquote t regard my career as finished.  I regard myself as an active sociologist, and I did things in retirement that I promised myself that I would do.  For example, I read all the latest books on the Crusades \endash 
 historical stuff.  I found that absolutely
