{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Yes.  I\rquote 
ve always had this interest.  I bought myself a telescope when I retired - well, no, actually only about five years ago.  The sky has cleared two or three times, and I\rquote ve had a few evenings out with it, and I absolutely love doing that.  I\rquote 
ve joined the North Wales Astronomy Society, I\rquote m a member of the Royal Astronomical Society.  Again, you know, it is so intellectually challenging once you get into cosmology.  And there are many parallels with sociology, because astronomers can
\rquote 
t do experiments.  They can only observe, and they can only observe partially, and bits of what they think they can see they now discover have been obscured.  And now, apparently, they can only see about 10% of the created universe.  That sounds very
 much like sociology to me!  So it\rquote s intellectually interesting: as is some amateur work I\rquote 
ve been doing with an Archaeology Group in North Wales.  And the challenge there, I think, is the relationship between theory and data, because archaeologists seem c
apable of finding a tiny fragment of something or other in the ground, and erecting an enormous historical theory on it \endash 
 rather like balancing a pyramid on its point!  Now, how do they do that?  What is the relationship between theory and data?  Well, you
 know, what do sociologists spend their time talking about?  The relationship between theory and data!  And how does theory drive you to seek certain kinds of data, and how do certain kinds of data force you to re-visit and re-think your theory?  Now, tha
t was all I was doing in Sparkbrook, for Heaven\rquote s sake!  You know?  And now I\rquote 
m stuck up on a windy hilltop in North Wales, where the rain blows horizontally, looking at a muddy hole in the ground, doing exactly the same thing!  So again, that\rquote s immensely stimulating and challenging.
