.  Now, they have got a good story to tell, but that\rquote s what we\rquote re always doing as}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5515476\charrsid14902524  sociologists \endash  it\rquote s the same.  }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 The other thing I do, and this is why I don\rquote t have much free time, is I run a little weather station in my back garden, and I\rquote 
ve just recently deposited ten years of weather records with the County Archives, and as an adjunct to that, and as part of it, I have a satellite rece
iving station. The origin of that is from my interest in radio, and that came partly from my father who, in the 1930s, had a Home Office licence to build radios \endash 
 because you had to have a licence to do it then, and it was taken away at the beginning of the War, they were all suspended \endash 
 and he was a great man building and repairing radios, with valves and batteries and all the rest of it.  I then became interested in radio in the Navy and I\rquote ve always listened to shortwave radio.  And then, gradually, throu
gh reading some of the radio literature, I realised that people were receiving signals from space, and I now have a set-up }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7567081\charrsid14902524 whereby}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524  I track and process data from the polar orbiting satellites, and receive a constant stream of data from the geo-stationary satellites over the equator. I
\rquote ve been on a number of on-line courses on meteorology, run by the European Meteorological Organisation for the Exploitation of Satellite Data, and so I\rquote m learning a bit of meteorology.  And that\rquote s like sociology too!  I mean, b
ecause you have data, you have theory, and you have technology, and advances in one stimulate development in the other two.  A lot of the modern meteorological theory is very very recent, because we\rquote 
ve only had the means of doing certain things because of 
high-flying aircraft in the Second World War, computers, satellites, and that has contributed to the development of theory.  So I receive all this data.  I try my hand at weather forecasting, so you learn all about probability.  I have great respect for w
eather forecasters, because they get it more right than I do!  And I also take on some of the critics who say they always get it wrong \endash  because they don\rquote 
t.  Actually, they get it right more often than not.  And that, again, you see, is just like sociology!  It\rquote s that engagement, but here it\rquote s not just data and theory with each driving the other, it\rquote 
s the capacity to process the data and more and more and more data.  For every kilometre square over the earth\rquote s surface is now fed into numerical modelling \endash  which is something I assure you I don\rquote t do, I\rquote 
d need a computer the size of the British Library to do it!  I just do old-fashioned weather forecasting, but with some very good data.  And every quarter I write a weather report for our community newspaper, and
 every month I produce a weather summary with a r\'e9sum\'e9
 of that month in the previous five years, for the Geography Department in our local secondary school.  So what is really fascinating is that sociology, meteorology, archaeology, astronomy, all have sim
ilar problems of theory and data, and, to some extent, of data processing.  They\rquote re \'85 they\rquote re quite different, but there\rquote s something there about the core of scientific enterprise \endash  I think.  I\rquote 
m not ever going to write a book about it, I\rquote m only going to talk about it!  Does that make sense?
