Yes!  Maybe we should draw this to a conclusion.  I wanted to ask a very general question, which is, if you look back at your life as a whole, both personal and professional, what would you say were the worst and the best things about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
It would be very hard for me to point to the worst things.  Sometimes my blood quite runs cold with thinking just how lucky I have been in my life.  It\rquote s almost as if I\rquote ve had a charmed life.  All the things that could have gone wrong 
\endash  particularly when you\rquote re at sea! \endash  and when you get caught in burning buildings as a sociologist, to get out. I have just been extraordinarily lucky.  The things I have done, and the things I have seen.  So I don\rquote 
t think there have been any really bad moments.  There have been bad periods. I suppose the highlights were taking command of a ship at sea \endash  I\rquote 
ll never forget that as long as I live!  It was wonderful!  Meeting Peter Worsley and John Rex, and knowing George McLeod.  Having a wonderful wife and two smashing children.
  I mean, what more could one ask for?  And here I am, 76 years old, and, touch wood, still pretty fit, charging across the Welsh hills on two good legs; but, I have been a sociologist.  If somebody said to me, \'93Who are you?\'94 or \'93What are you?
\'94 I would say, \'93I\rquote m a sociologist\'94.  That is what I am.  That is how I live.  You remember Max Weber talked about the Protestant being the monk in the world?  It\rquote s a bit like that.  I\rquote 
m a sociologist.  Sometimes, in my slightly more hysterical moments, I say I\rquote m really a sailor who happened to come ashore!  Because I sometimes wonder whether, deep down, I wouldn\rquote 
t have liked to stay at sea - not in the Navy, of course, with nuclear weapons.  But, no, I regard myself as a sociologist through and through.  Sometimes I describe myself as a professional sociologist, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid10690102\charrsid14902524 other times more modestly as a \lquote jobbing\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524  sociologist 
\endash  you know, \'93have skills will do jobs\'94.  So, in a sense, the highlight of my life has been my life.  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 
Of your professional life, do you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid3566045\charrsid14902524 Robert:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid7999863\charrsid14902524 Yeah. It\rquote 
s been the whole of my life.  The whole of my life has been a highlight.  Okay, a couple of odd failed love affairs early in life, but then we all have those \endash  I hope!  A very impoverished person who hasn\rquote 
t. We overcome them, and we grow from them.  But they don\rquote 
t loom over my life as sort of dreadful black spots on my life.  When I think, if I was to sit down and write down all the things I have done and seen, from commanding a ship, and flying an aeroplane, and travelling to the Far East, and teac
hing in India, I have done what many many people couldn\rquote t dream of, in a lifetime.  Any one bit of what I have done would be beyond the dreams of many people, and I just can\rquote 
t believe that I have been so lucky.  I keep on wondering whether hubris might kick in!  Maybe there is some terrible fate waiting for me!  I shall die a long painful lingering death or something.
